Ultra-fast. Ultra-reliable. Ultra-lightweight. It's no wonder the 85s are our most popular family. We pack them with a combination of customer-requested features and pair them with the .38 Special +P ammo making them powerful, easy to carry and lightning-quick to use. Plus P rated for duty use. This firearm is designed to handle high pressure loads under SAAMI specifications.

Taurus Security System (TSS)rs
Taurus family of semi-auto pistols all feature the Taurus Security System, which provides instant-ready defense with built-in ability to secure your pistol and make it inoperable at the turn of a key. When the Security System is engaged, the pistol cannot be fired or cocked and the gun's manual safety cannot be disengaged. As with our revolver Security System, the device is part of the firearm and cannot be lost, and the same special Security Key works for both the revolver and pistol Systems (two keys come with each gun). To engage: simply insert the Key into the button on the rear or side of the pistol and rotate one-quarter turn clockwise. This engages the Security System. The manual safety cannot be moved and the trigger cannot be pulled. To disengage: simply rotate the key one-quarter turn back. This releases the Security System, yet leaves the pistol's manual safety in the "safe" position until you are ready to release it yourself and fire the gun.

Transfer Bar
The transfer bar mechanism prevents the hammer from striking the firing pin unless the trigger is pulled fully to the rear.

O.C.G.A. Â§ 16-11-132
Possession of a handgun by a person under the age of 18 years

Georgia law only covers possession of handguns by those 
"Under" the age of 18 with varying circumstances, as well as those 21+. That means a person 18-20 can legally "posses" a handgun.

Furnishing pistol or revolver to person under the age of 18 years

This law relates to the sale of handguns in Georgia through a private party (you and I) sale. Once again, it only refers to those "under" the age of 18. (http://www.nraila.org/gun-laws/articles/2004/citizen%60s-guide-to-federal-firearms-law.aspx>

Having or carrying handguns, long guns, or other weapons; license requirement; exceptions for homes, motor vehicles, and other locations and conditions; penalties for violations

A person of age 18-20 is treated as an adult who does not have a Georgia Weapons Carry License, and must abide by those same rules. Those rules, in short, mean that the handgun may not leave the confines of my home (property of said home included), motor vehicle, and/or place of business

title: For Sale:  Ruger GP100 Match Champion
postcontent:
Ruger GP100 Match Champion

This revolver is about three months old, with a manufacture date of 12/14. A bit of background: I ordered a Match Champion from Tombstone Tactical in November of last year (11/14). When I received the revolver from my FFL, I noticed some cosmetic aberrations, but nothing too concerning. The action, however, was another matter.

The trigger was gritty and the single action sear actually produced a squeak during its "creepy" break. Needless to say, the revolver went back to Ruger with a strident letter of complaint. A few phone calls and two weeks later, I received a "hand-picked" Match Champion from their latest production run. The gun is what I expected it to be.
It has the "built like a tank" Ruger feel with a smooth and tuned action. Why do I mention all of this? Because you NEVER know what you are going to get when you buy sight unseen. Now, my story had a happy ending, but it was VERY frustrating and time consuming (an additional FFL transfer) with an uncertain resolution. If you elect to purchase this revolver, 
you will have a cream of the crop, GP100 Match Champion.

Why am I selling it? I'm just ready to move on to something else.

Details:

The revolver has had about 250 rounds put through it and most of these were 38 Special or light 357. I'm guessing maybe 50-75 moderate 357 loads -- not that it matters with a GP100. The gun is in like new condition and comes with the plastic case, paperwork, fired shell case (dated 12/15/14), and lock. I will also included a lightly used Hogue grip so you can mount that if you prefer cushy rubber over wood. Personally, I find the wood nice in esthetics and feel, but a bit punishing for magnum loads, hence the Hogue grip. The gun has been thoroughly cleaned and it is ready for inspection.

Price: $600
I am not interested in entertaining any trade offers for this firearm.
Lastly, I will split the cost of the requisite FFL transfer if the transaction is conducted on the Kitsap peninsula.

Thanks for reading.
